<h3 id="source-files">Source files</h3>

<p>Source files are in the form of HTML (<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.html</code>) or markdown (<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.md</code> or <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.markdown</code>). Jekyll compiles, builds, or renders markdown files into HTML files.</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.md</code>â†’ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.html</code></p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.markdown</code>â†’ <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.html</code></p>

<p>The built files are stored under <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">_site</code>. The default tree structure is:</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>_site
â”œâ”€â”€ about
â”œâ”€â”€ css
â”œâ”€â”€ images
â”œâ”€â”€ jekyll
â””â”€â”€ js

</code></pre></div></div>

<p>For details, refer to <a href="https://jekyllrb.com/docs/step-by-step/01-setup/#build">Jekyll &gt; DOCS &gt; GETTING STARTED &gt; Step by Step Tutorial &gt; Build</a>.</p>

<h3 id="source-files-1">Source files</h3>

<h4 id="indexhtml-1">index.html</h4>

